{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: System Coordination",
    "objective": "Explain the relationship between a TN-C-S supply arrangement and the distinct roles of bonding and CPCs in achieving ADS.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In a TN-C-S (PME) installation, the electricity supplier provides a combined Neutral and Earth (PEN) conductor to the property, which is then split at the intake.",
      "To ensure Automatic Disconnection of Supply (ADS) works correctly, the electrician must install both Main Protective Bonding to metallic services (like water pipes) and Circuit Protective Conductors (CPCs) to every individual circuit."
    ],
    "questionText": "Explain how the Main Protective Bonding and the CPC perform different roles to achieve safety in this TN-C-S system during a fault.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The TN-C-S system relies on the split PEN conductor at the intake. The Main Protective Bonding connects the metallic water pipes to the Main Earthing Terminal (MET) to maintain an equipotential zone (keeping all metal at the same voltage). In contrast, the CPC provides a dedicated path for fault current from a specific circuit back to the MET and the supplier's return path, which allows the protective device (fuse/MCB) to trip and disconnect the supply."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which conductor is there to keep pipes at the same voltage and which one is there to carry fault current from an appliance to trip the breaker."
  }
}

